        -:  116:// ========================================================================== //
        -:  117://                           Implementations
        -:  118:// ========================================================================== //
        -:  119:// ------------------------------------------------------------------------- //
        -:  120://                               Unique
        -:  121://               (_LIBCPP_TYPEINFO_COMPARISON_IMPLEMENTATION = 1)
        -:  122:// ------------------------------------------------------------------------- //
        -:  123:// This implementation of type_info assumes a unique copy of the RTTI for a
        -:  124:// given type inside a program. This is a valid assumption when abiding to the
        -:  125:// Itanium ABI (http://itanium-cxx-abi.github.io/cxx-abi/abi.html#vtable-components).
        -:  126:// Under this assumption, we can always compare the addresses of the type names
        -:  127:// to implement equality-comparison of type_infos instead of having to perform
        -:  128:// a deep string comparison.
        -:  129:// -------------------------------------------------------------------------- //
        -:  130://                             NonUnique
        -:  131://               (_LIBCPP_TYPEINFO_COMPARISON_IMPLEMENTATION = 2)
        -:  132:// -------------------------------------------------------------------------- //
        -:  133:// This implementation of type_info does not assume there is always a unique
        -:  134:// copy of the RTTI for a given type inside a program. For various reasons
        -:  135:// the linker may have failed to merge every copy of a types RTTI
        -:  136:// (For example: -Bsymbolic or llvm.org/PR37398). Under this assumption, two
        -:  137:// type_infos are equal if their addresses are equal or if a deep string
        -:  138:// comparison is equal.
        -:  139:// -------------------------------------------------------------------------- //
        -:  140://                          NonUniqueARMRTTIBit
        -:  141://               (_LIBCPP_TYPEINFO_COMPARISON_IMPLEMENTATION = 3)
        -:  142:// -------------------------------------------------------------------------- //
        -:  143:// This implementation is specific to ARM64 on Apple platforms.
        -:  144://
        -:  145:// This implementation of type_info does not assume always a unique copy of
        -:  146:// the RTTI for a given type inside a program. When constructing the type_info,
        -:  147:// the compiler packs the pointer to the type name into a uintptr_t and reserves
        -:  148:// the high bit of that pointer, which is assumed to be free for use under that
        -:  149:// ABI. If that high bit is set, that specific copy of the RTTI can't be assumed
        -:  150:// to be unique within the program. If the high bit is unset, then the RTTI can
        -:  151:// be assumed to be unique within the program.
        -:  152://
        -:  153:// When comparing type_infos, if both RTTIs can be assumed to be unique, it
        -:  154:// suffices to compare their addresses. If both the RTTIs can't be assumed to
        -:  155:// be unique, we must perform a deep string comparison of the type names.
        -:  156:// However, if one of the RTTIs is guaranteed unique and the other one isn't,
        -:  157:// then both RTTIs are necessarily not to be considered equal.
        -:  158://
        -:  159:// The intent of this design is to remove the need for weak symbols. Specifically,
        -:  160:// if a type would normally have a default-visibility RTTI emitted as a weak
        -:  161:// symbol, it is given hidden visibility instead and the non-unique bit is set.
        -:  162:// Otherwise, types declared with hidden visibility are always considered to have
        -:  163:// a unique RTTI: the RTTI is emitted with linkonce_odr linkage and is assumed
        -:  164:// to be deduplicated by the linker within the linked image. Across linked image
        -:  165:// boundaries, such types are thus considered different types.
        -:  166:
        -:  167:// This value can be overriden in the __config_site. When it's not overriden,
        -:  168:// we pick a default implementation based on the platform here.
        -:  169:#    ifndef _LIBCPP_TYPEINFO_COMPARISON_IMPLEMENTATION
        -:  170:
        -:  171:// Windows and AIX binaries can't merge typeinfos, so use the NonUnique implementation.
        -:  172:#      if defined(_LIBCPP_OBJECT_FORMAT_COFF) || defined(_LIBCPP_OBJECT_FORMAT_XCOFF)
        -:  173:#        define _LIBCPP_TYPEINFO_COMPARISON_IMPLEMENTATION 2
        -:  174:
        -:  175:// On arm64 on Apple platforms, use the special NonUniqueARMRTTIBit implementation.
        -:  176:#      elif defined(__APPLE__) && defined(__LP64__) && !defined(__x86_64__)
        -:  177:#        define _LIBCPP_TYPEINFO_COMPARISON_IMPLEMENTATION 3
        -:  178:
        -:  179:// On all other platforms, assume the Itanium C++ ABI and use the Unique implementation.
        -:  180:#      else
        -:  181:#        define _LIBCPP_TYPEINFO_COMPARISON_IMPLEMENTATION 1
        -:  182:#      endif
        -:  183:#    endif
